Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Diedra Raquel Green in court with attorney Ann M Heaps.  Defendant Diedra Raquel Green in custody.  Ronald Dague appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant changes plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Plea questionnaire received and filed. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  Court advised the defendant that as a convicted felon she may no longer use or possess any firearms; also she may not vote in any election until her civil rights have been restored.  Court further advised that if she is not a US citizen, deportation is possible. 

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements made by State, Defense and Defendant.
 
The Court sentenced defendant to serve 1 YEAR in the House of Corrections, straight time, with credit for 5 days time served.   Court STAYED sentence and placed the defendant on PROBATION for a period of 3 YEARS with the following conditions:
-Restitution set at $2,230.00 payable to Soup & Stock Market, joint and several with another other person(s) convicted of this offense.  Restitution to be collected during term of probation; nonpayment penalty shall result in a civil judgment
-Defendant to pay Court costs and all applicable surcharges and assessments are to be collected during term of probation; nonpayment penalty shall result in a civil judgment
-Defendant is to provide a DNA sample and pay the related surcharge to be collected during term of probation; nonpayment penalty shall result in a civil judgment
-No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause
-Cooperate with any correctional programs recommended
-Follow all rules of probation
-Pay all supervision fees; nonpayment penalty shall be a civil judgment 
-Cooperate with agent
-Obtain/maintain full-time employment or attend school on a full-time basis 
-Obtain GED or HSED
-No contact with Target, Walmart and Milwaukee Public Library
-AODA assessment and any recommended treatment
-Absolute sobriety with random urine screens and breathalyzers
-No alcohol or controlled substances
